[start section id="20103"]

#1 Multifocal colon cancer
Mr. Thomason is a 54-year-old man who approximately four and a-half years ago had a cecal cancer.  This is detected on a screening examination.  He underwent a laparoscopic right hemicolectomy at the Lawrence Health Center.  He has a family history of colon cancer with his maternal grandfather dying at age 37 of colon cancer.  By his recollection, there was some type of genetic testing that was done, but he was given the "all clear."  He had a follow-up colonoscopy one-year later that was normal.  He just recently presented for a three-year surveillance examination and was found to have a 50% obstructing mass in the transverse colon but not at the anastomosis.  More concerning is the finding of a 5-mm polyp 10-cm distal to this.  This also showed poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma in a 5-mm polyp.  These have been reviewed here.
He is currently asymptomatic.  He has no systemic symptoms.  He comes here for a second opinion regarding management.  He does smoke cigarettes.

